From: rajat@watson.ibm.com (Rajat Datta)
Subject: Re: X11R5 on Linux ?
Date: Tue, 31 Aug 1993 17:08:52 GMT

In article <CCMswz.n0M@dcs.qmw.ac.uk> bluejay@dcs.qmw.ac.uk (BUSARI) writes:
>Is it possible to install X11R5 on Linux ? I mean, instead of
>XFree86...I hear it's freely available --though it'd probably
>take up more disk space.
>But it'd be nice to have motif programs running on my PC.
>
>Since X11R5 is free (from what I here), then what's the point
>of having XFree86?  What's the difference (pros/cons) ?
>
>bluejay@dcs.qmw.ac.uk
>
>

XFree86 *is* X11R5.  To run X11 on any system, you have to port it.
You have to have device drivers for the display adapter(s) for
example.  You can also do optimizations for that specific
architecture.  That's what XFree86 is all about.  I believe XFree86
diffs are now distributed with the standard X11R5 tape (at least, it's
in the contrib directory at export.lcs.mit.edu).

Yes, X11R5 would take more disk space.  That's because you'd need the
source to do the port to Linux that the nice XFree86 people have
already done for you.

Motif does not come with X11R5 (nor with XFree86).  It's a separate
product sold typically to software vendors to include with their
systems.  You can buy Motif for Linux from several vendors that have
been mentioned from time to time (I don't remember their names
offhand).
-- 
rajat (rajat@watson.ibm.com)

