From: jon@robots.ox.ac.uk (Jon Tombs)
Subject: Re: X11R5 on Linux ?
Date: Tue, 31 Aug 1993 20:57:22 GMT

In article <CCMswz.n0M@dcs.qmw.ac.uk> bluejay@dcs.qmw.ac.uk (BUSARI) writes:
>Is it possible to install X11R5 on Linux ? I mean, instead of
>XFree86...I hear it's freely available --though it'd probably
>take up more disk space.

You seem to be under a very strange allusion, XFree86 _is_ X11R5 just very
much improved for i?86 architectures, and support for more operating systems.

>But it'd be nice to have motif programs running on my PC.

This has nothing to do with X11R5 or xfree86, you have to buy motif, atleast
one company (metrolink) sells motif for linux.

>Since X11R5 is free (from what I here), then what's the point
>of having XFree86?  What's the difference (pros/cons) ?

It runs on you machine. X11R5 doesn't support linux, nor does it have
compressed fonts, support for many vga cards, ... or is anywhere near as
fast.

Jon.

