From: dak@rama.informatik.rwth-aachen.de (David Kastrup)
Subject: Re: Linux and Corporate America
Date: 31 Aug 1993 22:05:43 GMT

iiitac@swan.pyr (Alan Cox) writes:

>As a followup to all of this the company I worked for picked gcc as a compiler
>for its quality, ditto for gdb. After that they picked Linux for a development
>OS. 
All in all, pretty good choices (although sort your systems in a way
that makes complete overinstallation easy. Separate the user disks/partitions
etc. from the system ones).

Watch out: gcc is a good quality tool, g++ is not. It has lots of bugs,
and although they are being fixed by Cygnus, releases are done that
infrequently as to make fast bug turnaround nonexistent. They collect
bug reports, though, and so some hope is there that next releases have
a considerable number of bugs fixed.
