From: ksh@prl.ufl.edu (Kevin S Ho)
Crossposted-To: comp.os.ms-windows.advocacy
Subject: Re: As nice as the Borland IDE?
Date: 31 Aug 1993 22:31:04 GMT

In article <JEM.93Aug30164816@delta.hut.fi>, jem@snakemail.hut.fi (Johan Myreen) writes:
|> In article <1993Aug24.134939.13206@infodev.cam.ac.uk> tjrc1@mbfs.bio.cam.ac.uk (Tim Cutts (Zoology)) writes:
|> 
        |> >Yes, but do you have anything as nice as a Borland IDE?
|> 
|> Yes, and even better, IMHO: Gnu Emacs. Emacs parses your error
|> messages just like the Borland IDE does, popping up the source file
|> with the cursor right on the error. Emacs can also interact with a
|> debugger, so you can single step through your code just like with the
|> Turbo debugger. You can step through your code while displaying the
|> output of your application in another window, be it a graphical or a
|> text application. With gdb you can even attach to an already running
|> process.
|> 
|> One thing I dislike about the Borland DOS IDE is that its use is based
|> so heavily on either pull-down menus or function keys. I don't like
|> either, menus are slow and function keys are placed so far away on the
|> keyboard that you tend to rest your palms on the other keys. Function
|> keys are also so nondescriptive: how do you associate F9 with compile
|> and F2 with save? Doing something as simple as finding out the value
|> of a variable in the debugger makes my blood pressure go up. The
|> gdb command line interface much better in this respect: just type
|> 'p var <RET>' to get the value printed.
|> 
|> Finding tags is also an invaluable feature of Emacs, which I don't
|> think has found its way to the Borland IDE yet. Emacs also has a
|> seamless interface to the RCS revision control system.
|> 
|> Personally I also hate the "Wordstar" editor in the IDE, but this is a
|> matter of personal taste (and the bindings can be redefined, I know).
|> But still I think Emacs is a more powerful editor.
|> 
|> Ok, the Borland IDE has some good points, like the built in project
|> management, which is perhaps a little bit nicer to use than doing it
|> by hand with makefiles. And the syntactic coloring in the Windows
Too bad, EMACS has that ;-)  get Emacs 19, and shove your nose into
some info nodes, it should be there I hope...

|> version is nice too. Emacs also does not have a GUI builder, but
What's that?

|> that's not built in into the Borland IDE either.


        KsH

