From: rvloon@cv.ruu.nl (Ronald van Loon)
Subject: Re: SLS considered harmful (wasRe: Bashing Peter MacDonald)
Date: Tue, 31 Aug 1993 22:14:08 GMT

In <1993Aug31.000806.7343.chiark.ijackson@nyx.cs.du.edu> ijackson@nyx.cs.du.edu (Ian Jackson) writes:

|"In article <1993Aug29.224238.5359@sol.UVic.CA> pmacdona@sanjuan (Peter MacDonald) writes:
|">     dd if=/dev/hda of=/dev/swap count=4096 bs=1k
|">The subsequent damage is blamed on SLS having a soft link for /dev/swap.
|"
|"And quite rightly too.
|"
|">This was just a harmless oversight, until someone followed the above bad 
|">advice.

Another oversight, in SLS 1.02, IMHO, was that libg.a is a symbolic link to
libc.a. When one installs new libraries from an extra-*.tar.gz file, it
depends on the order of the archive libraries which one ends up being the
final one - a libc.a of 2Mb, or conversely a libg.a of 450K (or whatever the
current size is).
